  "body": "### What is wrong?\r\n\r\nThe `ThroughputTracker` is emitting a `ValidationError` semi-regularly.\r\n\r\nHere are the relevant `DEBUG` logs\r\n\r\n```\r\n   DEBUG  07-17 16:47:52       chain  Beggining work for peer: ETHPeer <Node(0xa41d@127.0.0.1)> part: body\r\n   DEBUG  07-17 16:47:52       chain  Requesting 121 block bodies to ETHPeer <Node(0xa41d@127.0.0.1)>\r\n   DEBUG  07-17 16:47:52       chain  Beggining work for peer: ETHPeer <Node(0xa133@35.185.186.158)> part: body\r\n   DEBUG  07-17 16:47:52       chain  Requesting 1 block bodies to ETHPeer <Node(0xa133@35.185.186.158)>\r\n   DEBUG  07-17 16:47:52        peer  Could not complete handshake with <Node(0x399c7559da25f765b3590d974a852560b3e1467b5d926aac482debe2aaa39b5b6d35df92b41514fef5d3b6907ec9a2f21811c089f0ef8d14a2fc45a616bc720e@13.251.66.118:30305)>: HandshakeFailure('ETHPeer <Node(0x399c@13.251.66.118)> disconnected before completing handshake: too_many_peers',)\r\n   DEBUG  07-17 16:47:52       chain  Got Bodies for 121 blocks from ETHPeer <Node(0xa41d@127.0.0.1)>\r\n   DEBUG  07-17 16:47:52       chain  Got Bodies for 1 blocks from ETHPeer <Node(0xa133@35.185.186.158)>\r\n   DEBUG  07-17 16:47:52       chain  Completing work for peer: ETHPeer <Node(0xa133@35.185.186.158)> part: BlockPartEnum.body\r\n   DEBUG  07-17 16:47:52        peer  ETHPeer <Node(0xa41d@127.0.0.1)> disconnected: useless_peer\r\n    INFO  07-17 16:47:52        peer  ETHPeer <Node(0xa41d@127.0.0.1)> finished, removing from pool\r\n   DEBUG  07-17 16:47:52        peer  Could not complete handshake with <Node(0xcce09bd1ab7c00ee07613a4b40a84f858e85611ec98d9f836da19074777aca2f1c97583500197d6c5d969444d1d9b8bcc02afff4442f608b203d8447653b4f63@18.182.24.209:30303)>: HandshakeFailure('ETHPeer <Node(0xcce0@18.182.24.209)> disconnected before completing handshake: too_many_peers',)\r\n   DEBUG  07-17 16:47:52        peer  Could not complete handshake with <Node(0xac22b0fc0e25febcfcc81040fffe67d663fa492635b0f7a96061e2ed6ae3771714b542395a5df76c97e20068f4cfb66056dd04af96f6f041345f382e41ee5db2@149.28.108.149:30303)>: HandshakeFailure('ETHPeer <Node(0xac22@149.28.108.149)> disconnected before completing handshake: too_many_peers',)\r\n   DEBUG  07-17 16:47:53       chain  Completing work for peer: ETHPeer <Node(0xa41d@127.0.0.1)> part: BlockPartEnum.body\r\n   ERROR  07-17 16:47:53  base_events  Task exception was never retrieved\r\nfuture: <Task finished coro=<BaseHeaderChainSyncer.sync() done, defined at /Users/piper/sites/py-evm/p2p/chain.py:156> exception=ValidationError('Cannot end the ThroughputTracker without starting it',)>\r\nTraceback (most recent call last):\r\n  File \"/Users/piper/sites/py-evm/p2p/chain.py\", line 169, in sync\r\n    await self._sync(peer)\r\n  File \"/Users/piper/sites/py-evm/p2p/chain.py\", line 230, in _sync\r\n    head_number = await self._process_headers(peer, headers)\r\n  File \"/Users/piper/sites/py-evm/p2p/chain.py\", line 376, in _process_headers\r\n    BlockPartEnum.body,\r\n  File \"/Users/piper/sites/py-evm/p2p/chain.py\", line 452, in _download_block_parts\r\n    self._get_peer_stats(peer, part_name).complete_work(work_size)\r\n  File \"/Users/piper/sites/py-evm/p2p/utils.py\", line 84, in complete_work\r\n    raise ValidationError(\"Cannot end the ThroughputTracker without starting it\")\r\neth.exceptions.ValidationError: Cannot end the ThroughputTracker without starting it\r\n```\r\n\r\nThese logs show that the node `0xa41d` disconnects shortly after sending through a requested batch of work.  The disconnect is processed before the received bodies are processed, which causes `deregister_peer` to be called.  This causes the `ThroughputTracker` for the given peer to be cleared.  Then, when the work is received and processed, it encounters a fresh (lazily created) `ThroughputTracker` which has not had work started on it, causing the exception.\r\n\r\n### How can it be fixed\r\n\r\nMaybe:\r\n\r\n1. silently ignore this when it happens (has high likelyhood of silencing real errors)\r\n2. don't clear trackers immediately on disconnect\r\n3. don't clear trackers at all and instead use a TTL expiration mechanism to automatically clear trackers which are *old*.\r\n4. modify the trackers to not be singletons but to be able to track multiple in-flight requests concurrently.  Key the requests based on some kind of unique-ish request identifier based on what was requested to ensure that the `complete_work` is being called on the actual request that started the work.  use a TTL mechanism to expire timed out requests as well as timed out trackers.\r\n\r\nLast idea in list is my favorite",
